I. Anatomy of Conflicts

Subjective phenomena, as opposed to what?

Physical objects could be considered objective phenomena. However, since humans typically only interact with physical objects when we imbue them with meaning, people may also subjectively experience “objective phenomena”.

Social construction means anything goes?

While experiences can be considered ultimately subjective, it isn’t right to say that “anything goes”. This is because shared meanings, symbols beliefs and norms are in a constant state of negotiation and validation within the sociocultural frame work. An individual can change their point of view to be very different from those around them but are still impacted by the beliefs, values and norms of all the other people in the society that do not see things the same way. An individual can change change their point of to “anything goes” but this may have limited impact on the social fabric around them.

Are all experiences, meanings, preferences equally valid?

They are only equally valid from a particular objective view. From any one sociocultural group’s point of view, there may be hierarchies of experience, meaning, and preferences that are validated through social negotiation and historical context.

What is Power?

the capacity to impose a specific definition of reality which is disadvantageous to others or to limit other’s autonomy. Could be a imposition of a specific landscape

II. Science, Politics and Environmental Controversies

Based on the linear model of science, what are the sources of conservation conflicts?

Advocacy positions and politicization

What does Bjorn Lomborg and his critics tell us about the role of science in understanding environmental problems?

Belief in the linear model. They believe that you need to “follow what the science is telling us” and do what the data tells you to do. They believe that science will inform good policy without the need for discussion of values.

What is the excess of objectivity, with examples from the readings

It is the idea that science is ’’too good at it’s job” and creates an overwhelming amount of contextually validated knowledge within a multitude of disciplines. This production in combination with the vast complexity of the natural world leads to such a large set of facts that , in essence, one could support almost any position by filtering these facts from a particular point of view or with a specific motivation in mind.

One example is how Lomberg and his critics both cite statistical studies which come to differing conclusions. They both say they are following the data, but which data becomes quite critical.

Another example is how increasingly technical statistical analysis of the Bush Gore US election at best produced increasing amounts of uncertainty as possible approaches to recounting votes could only be contextually validated within the specific disciplines of psychology, statistics, etc…

With examples from oceanographers and GMO scientists, what is the role of values in science?

What is meant by a normative framework?

“For Lovejoy, the process starts when “researchers identify a potential problem,” but the recognition that something is a “problem” demands a pre-existing framework of values and interests within which problems can be recognized. And Pimentel’s “wary outlook” (not to mention Lomborg’s rosy one) presupposes some expectations of what the world ought to look like in the ﬁrst place.” (Sarewitz, 2004)

“This alignment of disciplinary perspective and worldly interests is critically important in understanding environmental controversies, because it shows that stripping out conflicts of interest and ideological commitments to look at “what the science is really telling us” can be a meaningless exercise.” (Sarewitz, 2004)

“it might be most accurate to look at the scientific debate not as tainted by values and interests, but as an explicit—if arcane—negotiation of the conflict between competing values and interests embodied by competing disciplines.” (Sarewitz, 2004)

“To summarize thus far: central to the idea that science can help resolve environmental controversies is the expectation that science can help us understand current conditions under which our decisions are being made, and the potential future consequences of those decisions. This expectation must confront the proliferation of available facts that can be used to build competing pictures of current and future conditions, and the embeddedness of such facts in disciplinary perspectives that carry with them normative implications.” (Sarewitz, 2004)

What are the dimensions of collective action frames?

  1. Problem Identification, Locus of Attribution. The most obvious way in which collective action frames vary is in terms of the problems or issues addressed and the corresponding direction of attribution.

  2. **Flexibility and Rigidity, Inclusivity and Exclusivity. **Collective action frames may vary in the degree to which they are relatively exclusive, rigid, inelastic, and restricted or relatively inclusive, open, elastic, and elaborated in terms of the number of themes or ideas they incorporate and articulate

  3. Variation in Interpretive Scope and Influence

  4. Resonance:

    1. Frame Credibility

      1. Frame Consistency

        refers to the congruency between an SMO’s beliefs, claims, and actions.

      2. Empirical Credibility

        refers to the apparent fit between the framings and events in the world.

      3. Credibility of the Claimsmaker

    2. Relative Salience

      1. Centrality

        has to do with how essential the values, and ideas associated with movement frames are to the lives of the targets of mobilization.

      2. Experiential commensurability

        is when the framining is consistent with the personal experiences of the target.

      3. Narrative Fidelity

        is how well the frame firts with the existing cultural myths, ethos, or inherent ideology.

What are the general attirbutes of a Community Forest?

  • Decision making and control that is separate from state forestry agencies
  • Natural and plantation forest management for local benefits
  • Multiple-use management
  • Long-term ecological health

What is Public Participation?

“Various forms of direct public involvement where people, individually or through organized groups, can exchange information, express opinions and articulate interests, and have the potential to influence decisions or the outcome of specific forestry issues.” (Parkins, 2024) …especially the “potential to influence” aspect

What are some issues frequently encountered in Public Participation?

  • process has been captured by experts or industry
